english:
  title: On the Honeybee
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Humans and creatures alike receive from Heaven the same fundamental nature. Though humans are by nature superior to all things, there are many tasks that creatures accomplish which humans cannot. Why is this? Because human endeavor is broad yet scattered, lacking focus. Thus in matters we ought to pursue, we fail to achieve the ultimate perfection. The nature of creatures, though limited and constrained, knows only what serves eating and survival. Yet in that narrow sphere where their nature shines clear, they do not lose what Heaven bestowed as their origin. Where duty calls, they give their lives without hesitation.

    Consider the sovereign and subject among bees and ants, the father and son among tigers and wolves, the distinction between male and female in the osprey, the gratitude shown by the wolf and otter toward their origin—all emerge naturally from their inborn nature. And their ability to meet trials and changes flows equally from that same nature.

    In Milyang lived a beekeeper. Among all his bees, one stood noticeably larger—the queen bee—yet the keeper did not know this. One day she flew in from outside, and thinking her a strange creature come to harm his bees, he killed her. Days passed, and all the bees gathered in one place, clustered close together, and died. The keeper wept tears of sorrow.

    Hearing this tale, I wept and spoke thus: "The honeybee is but a lowly insect. All it knows of its queen is to follow her flight, dwell in her hive, and make honey together in that shared home. Yet even this humble creature repays her with its death. How much more should a minister, who shares one body with his lord, who together enjoys Heaven's station, who together partakes of Heaven's bounty, who shares both fortune and misfortune, life and death—how much more should such a one hold it as duty to die for his lord without a second thought?

    Long ago, Tian Heng refused to serve the Han and went to his death. Two of his followers died with him, and five hundred others on an island, hearing of his death, also perished. The historians of Han praised them greatly. Yet in Tang, Wang Gui and Wei Zheng did not die in the rebellion of Jiancheng but followed Taizong instead. The ancient scholars condemned them for this. In later generations, countless ministers have fallen short even of the honeybee.

    When the times shift and fortunes change, when some alter their words and turn their faces, forgetting their lord to serve his enemies, earning contempt for all ages—of such ones we need not speak. Yet let the smallest creature be the mirror for all who serve: in its unwavering loyalty dwells a lesson for us all."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Tian Heng was a Chinese general who rebelled against the Han Dynasty and eventually died, with his followers choosing to die with him rather than surrender.
  - key: ''
    value: Wang Gui and Wei Zheng were officials of the Tang Dynasty who switched their allegiance from the heir apparent Jiancheng to his brother, the future emperor Taizong, after a succession dispute.
  - key: ''
    value: The osprey (雎鳩) is referenced in the Book of Odes as a symbol of marital harmony and propriety between partners.
